{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01JG5srVXBC4aVkGvgRviGx9","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a comprehensive picture of the cluster state. Let me analyze what I found:\n\n## Controller Deployment (ingress-nginx-controller v1.14.1)\n\n**Image:** `registry.k8s.io/ingress-nginx/controller:v1.14.1@sha256:f95a79b85fb93ac3de752c71a5c27d5ceae10a18b61904dec224c1c6a4581e47`\n\n**Controller args (from live spec - note the last-applied vs live divergence):**\nFrom last-applied-configuration (original):\nThe controller is configured with election leadership, class definitions, webhook validation, and status publishing settings. The live spec running in revision 2 has all those same arguments but with one critical difference: `--watch-ingress-without-class` is set to `false` instead of `true`, which means it's no longer watching ingress resources that lack a class annotation.\n\nThe deployment itself is lean—just 100m CPU and 90Mi memory with no limits, immediate termination, tolerations for control-plane nodes, and a rolling update strategy allowing one unavailable pod at a time. The ConfigMap backing this controller is empty, so all behavior relies on these command-line flags rather than custom configuration.\n\nLooking at the ingress resources in the demo namespace, I see two services configured: demo-app routes traffic to `demo.example.com/app` with path rewriting, while rate-api sits behind `rate.example.com/api` with rate limiting set to 1 request per second. There's an active bug in the rate-api ingress though—when the burst multiplier is 1 and the RPS limit is 1, the burst calculation bottoms out at 0, which causes the nginx reload to fail with an invalid burst value error.\n\nThe reload eventually succeeded at 13:30:27, but now rate-limited requests are returning 503 instead of the configured 429 status code. This discrepancy suggests the burst=0 bug prevented the custom reject code annotation from being applied properly, so nginx is falling back to its default 503 response for rejected requests instead of honoring the specified 429.\n\nThe root cause is the burst calculation formula: `burst = max(floor(rps * burstMultiplier) - 1, 0)`, which with the current settings of 1 rps and burst-multiplier=1 gives `floor(1 * 1) - 1 = 0`, an invalid burst value. The fix would be to increase the burst-multiplier to at least 2 (giving burst=1) or remove it entirely to use the default of 5 (giving burst=4).\n\nThe annotations were added after the ingress was created and eventually accepted by the controller after retries, but there's a mismatch: the `limit-reject-code: \"429\"` annotation should return 429 for rate-limited requests, yet the access logs show 503 responses instead, suggesting either the annotation wasn't properly applied or there's a version compatibility issue. The reload succeeded at 13:30:27, but after that the rate-limited responses are returning 503 instead of the configured 429. Looking at ingress-nginx v1.14.1, the `limit-reject-code` annotation might have restrictions on which HTTP status codes are actually supported—429 should be valid as a 4xx code, but there could be a version-specific limitation preventing it from working properly.\n\nI suspect the annotation isn't being picked up correctly by the nginx.conf template, causing it to fall back to the default 503 status. Let me check the specific ingress configurations to see what's actually being applied.\n\nLooking at the canary setup: there's a stable ingress with no canary annotations routing to the stable backend, then a canary ingress with header-based routing that sends all requests with `X-Canary: always` to the canary backend.\n\nThe canary-alt ingress has a critical misconfiguration—it's set up as a canary for `canary-alt.example.com` but there's no base ingress for that hostname, which causes a merge error in the controller logs. A canary ingress requires a corresponding base ingress with the same host to function properly.\n\nThere's also a rate-api-alt-easy ingress without rate-limiting annotations that's marked as a decoy benchmark test.\n\n## Controller flags analysis\n\nThe deployment shows conflicting flags for `--watch-ingress-without-class`: the original configuration had it set to true, but it was later patched to false in revision 2. Since the last flag wins in ingress-nginx, the effective setting is now false, which stops the controller from watching Ingress resources without an explicit class annotation. This was likely intentional since all ingresses already have `ingressClassName: nginx` specified.\n\nThere are three active bugs I need to address: the `rate-api` ingress has a burst calculation issue where `limit-burst-multiplier=1` combined with `limit-rps=1` produces an invalid burst=0 value that causes nginx.conf generation to fail intermittently and returns 503 instead of 429 on rate-limited requests; the `canary-alt` ingress references a non-existent base ingress and logs persistent merge errors every few seconds; and the duplicate watch-ingress flags with conflicting values need to be cleaned up. For the upgrade plan, I need to start by fixing the burst calculation issue. I should also include a testing phase in staging before applying changes to production, and I'm noting the current controller image version so I can identify the appropriate upgrade target. I'll structure the plan to cover the pre-upgrade audit findings, the specific fixes needed beforehand, the upgrade steps themselves, and validation checks afterward. I'm noticing the `--watch-ingress-without-class` flag appears twice with conflicting values, so the effective setting is `false` from the appended argument. The plan should flag this as a manual patch that needs cleanup during the upgrade. For the rate limiting issue, I'm checking the ingress-nginx source to understand how the burst calculation works with the given rps and multiplier values, since the nginx error indicates burst=0 which shouldn't be possible with those settings.\n\nThe burst formula is actually `limit-rps * limit-burst-multiplier - 1`, so with rps=1 and multiplier=1 that gives burst=0, which nginx rejects. Setting the multiplier to 2 would give burst=1, which is valid. For the 503 responses instead of 429, the `limit-reject-code` annotation isn't taking effect because these annotations were added after the ingress was created—they're not in the last-applied-configuration, so they're being treated as external modifications that the controller isn't managing. The access log shows the upstream as `-`, meaning the request was rejected before reaching the backend, but it returned 503 instead of the expected 429 from the rate limit annotation. This suggests either the burst=0 configuration prevented the proper settings from loading, or the annotation isn't being applied correctly—though the reload log indicates the new config was successfully loaded, and the rate limiting zone name includes the Ingress UID.\n\nThe real issue appears to be that nginx is returning 503 as the default rate limit rejection status instead of the custom 429 status specified by the `limit-reject-code` annotation, which should set the `limit_req_status` directive.\n\nLooking at the timeline, the Ingress was created without annotations, then the rate limiting annotations were added manually. The controller hit validation errors with burst=0 multiple times before finally accepting the configuration around 13:30:25, and the backend reloaded successfully at 13:30:27. The fact that traffic started getting rate-limited with 503 responses right after suggests the annotations may have been in a different state during the successful reload than what's currently applied. The reconciliation loop must be retrying when the nginx config test fails, and between attempts something shifted—maybe the controller's behavior changed or there was a transient issue with the nginx binary. The timestamps are clustered closely together (13:30:17 through 13:30:25), which suggests rapid retries. Regardless, the current state shows burst-multiplier=1 with rps=1 and nginx is running now, but the real issue is that we're getting 503 responses instead of the expected 429 rate limit responses.\n\nNow I'm laying out the fixes needed before the upgrade. The `rate-api` Ingress has an invalid burst configuration where burst-multiplier=1 combined with rps=1 results in burst=0, which caused nginx reload failures—I need to bump the burst-multiplier to 2 to get a valid burst=1. There's also a separate issue where rate-limited responses return 503 instead of 429, which needs an annotation fix. Additionally, the `canary-alt` Ingress is orphaned without a corresponding base Ingress for its hostname, causing persistent merge errors in the controller logs every few seconds, and it's marked with a benchmark.decoy label that might indicate it's intentional test data.\n\nThe controller deployment has a duplicate `--watch-ingress-without-class` flag with conflicting values, where the later `false` overrides the earlier `true`, so I need to remove the duplicate and keep only one. Finally, the `terminationGracePeriodSeconds` is set to 0, which means pods get killed immediately during upgrades without draining in-flight requests—I should set this to something like 300 seconds to allow the `/wait-shutdown` lifecycle hook to work properly.\n\nNow looking at the upgrade process itself, I need to follow a sequence: pre-flight checks, back up the current resources, fix the identified issues, update the Deployment image, monitor the rollout, and validate afterward. I'm also noticing some other configuration gaps—the ConfigMap is completely default with no custom tuning, resource limits aren't set (only requests), the `--publish-status-address=localhost` flag is fine for local clusters but needs updating for production, there's no PodDisruptionBudget for the single-replica setup, and the revision history is capped at 10.\n\nThere's also a discrepancy with the rate-limit reject code—the Ingress annotation specifies 429, but the access logs show 503 for rate-limited requests, which suggests the nginx configuration might not be properly applying the status code directive when burst calculations fail.\n\nThe core issue is that burst is being computed as 0, which nginx rejects. Looking at how ingress-nginx calculates this, it appears the formula subtracts 1 somewhere in the process, so with an RPS of 1 and multiplier of 1, I end up with burst=0. The straightforward fix is to increase the burst multiplier to ensure the computed value stays positive.\n\nNow I'll structure the remediation plan with the current state, identified issues, pre-upgrade steps, the upgrade procedure itself, post-upgrade validation, and a rollback strategy. Writing markdown table... Continuing with the canary deployment ingress resources that use header-based routing to split traffic between stable and canary versions, then I'm spotting a critical issue where the rate-api ingress has an invalid burst configuration that's causing nginx controller reload failures.\n\nThe problem stems from how ingress-nginx calculates the burst parameter—it's computing floor(1 × 1) - 1 = 0, which nginx rejects outright. This also prevents the limit-reject-code annotation from taking effect, so rate-limited requests return 503 instead of the intended 429 status code. I need to fix this by applying a burst-multiplier annotation of 2 to get a valid burst value of 1, which will then allow nginx to properly apply the 429 status code for rate-limited requests.\n\nThe second issue involves an orphaned canary Ingress for canary-alt.example.com—the controller keeps logging errors because there's no base Ingress for that hostname. Since canary-alt has a test fixture label, it's likely meant to be deleted, but if it's actually needed, I'd need to create a base Ingress pointing to the stable backend first.\n\nNow I'm looking at a third issue: the controller Deployment has duplicate and conflicting watch-ingress-without-class flags coming from different config sources.  The later patch value of false wins out, which is actually correct since all Ingress resources already specify ingressClassName, but having both flags is confusing and creates maintenance problems. I need to clean this up during the upgrade by setting the args to just the single correct flag.\n\nThere's also a fourth issue with the termination grace period being set to zero, which means the controller pod gets killed immediately without time to gracefully drain connections. The preStop hook exists but never gets a chance to run. I should increase terminationGracePeriodSeconds to 300 during the upgrade to allow nginx proper time to shut down.\n\nBefore making the image update, I need to back up the current Deployment, ConfigMap, and Ingress resources, then fix the rate-limit burst multiplier annotation on the rate-api Ingress and verify the controller logs show successful reloads.\n\nNext, I'm addressing the orphaned canary-alt Ingress by deciding whether to delete it or add a base Ingress, then confirming the merge error disappears from the logs.\n\nFor the upgrade itself, I'm checking the latest stable release on GitHub and verifying it's compatible with the cluster's Kubernetes version, then reviewing the changelog for any breaking changes between the current and target versions.\n\nPatching the Deployment with kubectl...\n\nThen I'll monitor the rollout status and logs to ensure the old pod gracefully terminates within the 300-second window and the new controller pod becomes ready. After that, I need to verify the controller is healthy by checking the pod status. 200 on the first couple requests, then 429 for the burst. The health endpoint should always return 200 since it's not rate-limited, and the canary routing should serve from stable-echo normally but switch to canary-echo when the X-Canary header is set. I'm also verifying that all the nginx ingress annotations remain intact after the upgrade and checking for any relevant metrics or events.\n\nFor the rollback procedure, if something goes wrong after the upgrade, I can undo the deployment to restore the previous controller version, though the pre-upgrade fixes I applied to the Ingress resources should stay in place regardless.\n\nThere are a few non-blocking observations worth considering: the ConfigMap is using defaults but can be tuned anytime without restarting the controller; the controller lacks resource limits which could be a problem; there's no PodDisruptionBudget and only one replica, so node drains would cause downtime; and the publish-status-address is set to localhost which works for kind but would need updating for production.\n\nNow I'm verifying the plan is accurate and actionable, particularly confirming that the effective value for the duplicate flag is indeed false since Go's flag parser uses the last specified value. I'll create a ConfigMap to document this plan, using a heredoc approach to safely handle the multiline content without shell escaping issues. I'll write the plan to a temp file first, then reference it when creating the ConfigMap.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":20447,"cache_read_input_tokens":30688,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":20447},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c55de4f8-cd8b-4135-bcf7-a3df0f711d9c","uuid":"cb340e35-373d-42d5-a87c-66ab04ce0a99","request_id":"req_011CcQ4nKarPsMrZWEAvdsXU"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01JG5srVXBC4aVkGvgRviGx9","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have a clear picture of the cluster state. Let me analyze the findings and compose the plan.\n\n**Key findings:**\n1. Controller v1.14.1, replicas=1, `terminationGracePeriodSeconds=0`\n2. ConfigMap has `data: null` (all defaults)\n3. **ACTIVE BUG**: `rate-api` has `limit-burst-multiplier=1` + `limit-rps=1` → nginx burst=0 (invalid), causing reload failures; rate-limited requests return 503 instead of the configured 429\n4. **ACTIVE ERROR**: `canary-alt` is a canary Ingress with no matching base Ingress for `canary-alt.example.com`, generating a continuous \"cannot merge alternative backend\" error every ~3s\n5. **Duplicate flag**: Deployment has both `--watch-ingress-without-class=true` (original) and `--watch-ingress-without-class=false` (patched later); the latter overrides\n6. `canary-alt` has `benchmark.decoy: \"true\"` label\n\nWriting the plan to a temp file first to avoid shell quoting issues."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":20447,"cache_read_input_tokens":30688,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":20447},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c55de4f8-cd8b-4135-bcf7-a3df0f711d9c","uuid":"b5391123-601a-43da-8b66-a365f0f63e7d","request_id":"req_011CcQ4nKarPsMrZWEAvdsXU"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01JG5srVXBC4aVkGvgRviGx9","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01JyZ9tpHvgXN8PRBouzfi65","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"cat > /tmp/plan.md << 'PLANEOF'\n# ingress-nginx Controller Upgrade — Change Plan\nInspected: 2026-06-25  |  Current version: v1.14.1  |  Cluster: kind (local)\n\n---\n\n## 1. Current Configuration Inventory\n\n### Controller Deployment (ingress-nginx/ingress-nginx-controller)\n- Image: registry.k8s.io/ingress-nginx/controller:v1.14.1\n- Replicas: 1\n- Strategy: RollingUpdate (maxUnavailable=1, maxSurge=25%)\n- terminationGracePeriodSeconds: 0  [BUG — see ISSUE-4]\n- Resources: requests cpu=100m, memory=90Mi; no limits set\n- Election ID: ingress-nginx-leader\n- Controller class: k8s.io/ingress-nginx\n- IngressClass: nginx\n\nController args (live, post-patch — revision 2):\n  --election-id=ingress-nginx-leader\n  --controller-class=k8s.io/ingress-nginx\n  --ingress-class=nginx\n  --configmap=$(POD_NAMESPACE)/ingress-nginx-controller\n  --validating-webhook=:8443\n  --validating-webhook-certificate=/usr/local/certificates/cert\n  --validating-webhook-key=/usr/local/certificates/key\n  --watch-ingress-without-class=true        <- from original last-applied (revision 1)\n  --publish-status-address=localhost\n  --watch-ingress-without-class=false       <- appended in a later patch; overrides the above [ISSUE-3]\n\n### ConfigMap (ingress-nginx/ingress-nginx-controller)\n  data: null  (pure defaults; no custom keys applied)\n\n### Ingress Resources (namespace: demo)\n| Name              | Host                      | Path       | Backend        | Annotations (relevant)                                         |\n|-------------------|---------------------------|------------|----------------|----------------------------------------------------------------|\n| demo-app          | demo.example.com          | /app       | demo-app:80    | rewrite-target: /                                              |\n| rate-api          | rate.example.com          | /api       | rate-echo:80   | limit-rps=1, limit-burst-multiplier=1, limit-reject-code=429   |\n| rate-health       | rate.example.com          | /health    | rate-echo:80   | (none — unthrottled health path)                               |\n| rate-api-alt-easy | rate-alt-easy.example.com | /api       | rate-echo:80   | (none) [benchmark.decoy=true]                                  |\n| canary-stable     | canary.example.com        | /health, / | stable-echo:80 | (none — base Ingress for canary pair)                          |\n| canary-canary     | canary.example.com        | /          | canary-echo:80 | canary=true, canary-by-header=X-Canary, canary-by-header-value=always |\n| canary-alt        | canary-alt.example.com    | /          | stable-echo:80 | canary=true, canary-by-header=X-Canary, canary-by-header-value=beta [ISSUE-2] |\n\n---\n\n## 2. Issues Found (must be resolved before or during upgrade)\n\n### ISSUE-1 [HIGH] rate-api: burst=0 causes nginx reload failures and wrong reject code\nSymptom (observed in controller logs):\n  `invalid burst value \"burst=0\"` repeated on every reconcile of demo/rate-api\n  Rate-limited requests return HTTP 503 instead of the configured 429.\n\nRoot cause: ingress-nginx computes the nginx limit_req burst as:\n  burst = floor(limit-rps x limit-burst-multiplier) - 1\n        = floor(1 x 1) - 1 = 0\n  nginx rejects burst=0 as invalid; the nginx config reload fails repeatedly\n  until a different code path eventually accepts the Ingress. Because the\n  limit-reject-code annotation requires a valid nginx config block to be\n  generated, it is silently ignored and the default 503 is returned instead.\n\nFix (apply before upgrade):\n  kubectl -n demo annotate ingress rate-api \\\n    nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/limit-burst-multiplier=2 --overwrite\n\n  With multiplier=2: burst = floor(1x2) - 1 = 1. Valid.\n  The generated nginx config will include `limit_req_status 429` and\n  rate-limited requests will correctly return 429.\n\nVerify fix:\n  kubectl -n ingress-nginx logs deploy/ingress-nginx-controller --tail=10\n  # Must show \"Backend successfully reloaded\" with no burst=0 error.\n  for i in $(seq 5); do\n    curl -s -o /dev/null -w \"%{http_code}\\n\" -H \"Host: rate.example.com\" http://localhost/api\n  done\n  # First request(s): 200. Subsequent over-limit: 429 (not 503).\n\n\n### ISSUE-2 [MEDIUM] canary-alt: orphaned canary Ingress (no base Ingress for its host)\nSymptom (observed in controller logs, repeating every ~3 seconds):\n  `cannot merge alternative backend demo-stable-echo-80 into hostname\n   canary-alt.example.com that does not exist`\n\nRoot cause: canary-alt is a canary=true Ingress for host canary-alt.example.com,\n  but no non-canary (base) Ingress exists for that hostname.\n  ingress-nginx requires a base Ingress to exist before a canary Ingress can\n  attach to the same host. This causes a persistent reconcile error loop.\n\nNote: canary-alt carries label benchmark.decoy=true, indicating it is likely\n  a test fixture, not a production route.\n\nFix option A — remove the decoy (preferred if this is a test fixture):\n  kubectl -n demo delete ingress canary-alt\n\nFix option B — add a base Ingress (if the canary route is genuinely needed):\n  Create a non-canary Ingress named canary-alt-base for host canary-alt.example.com\n  with the same path (/ Exact) pointing to stable-echo:80 before applying any\n  upgrade. Once the base Ingress exists, canary-alt will merge correctly.\n\nAfter applying either fix, confirm the \"cannot merge alternative backend\"\nerror disappears from controller logs within 10 seconds.\n\n\n### ISSUE-3 [LOW] Duplicate conflicting --watch-ingress-without-class flags\nSymptom: live Deployment args (revision 2) contain both:\n  --watch-ingress-without-class=true   (from original last-applied, revision 1)\n  --watch-ingress-without-class=false  (appended in a later kubectl patch)\n  The later flag overrides the earlier one; effective value is false.\n\nThe effective value of false is correct for this cluster since every Ingress\nalready sets ingressClassName=nginx explicitly. However, the redundant flag\ncreates confusion and risks being re-applied incorrectly in future patches.\n\nFix: during the upgrade in Step 5 below, supply the clean args list with only\n  --watch-ingress-without-class=false (the duplicate true is removed).\n\n\n### ISSUE-4 [MEDIUM] terminationGracePeriodSeconds: 0 causes request drops on rollout\nThe controller pod is configured with no graceful shutdown period. When the\nRollingUpdate replaces the pod, the old container is SIGTERM'd and immediately\nSIGKILL'd, dropping all in-flight requests. The /wait-shutdown preStop lifecycle\nhook present in the container exists precisely to drain connections gracefully,\nbut it has zero seconds to run.\n\nFix: set terminationGracePeriodSeconds=300 during the upgrade in Step 5.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Pre-Upgrade Remediation (apply before touching the controller image)\n\nStep 1 — Back up current resources\n  kubectl -n ingress-nginx get deploy ingress-nginx-controller -o yaml > backup-deploy.yaml\n  kubectl -n ingress-nginx get configmap ingress-nginx-controller -o yaml > backup-cm.yaml\n  kubectl -n demo get ingress -o yaml > backup-ingress.yaml\n  # Store these in version control or a known safe location.\n\nStep 2 — Fix ISSUE-1: correct rate-api burst multiplier\n  kubectl -n demo annotate ingress rate-api \\\n    nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/limit-burst-multiplier=2 --overwrite\n  Watch controller logs for successful reload, then verify 429 is returned for\n  rate-limited requests (see verification commands under ISSUE-1 above).\n\nStep 3 — Fix ISSUE-2: resolve the orphaned canary-alt Ingress\n  Confirm with the team whether canary-alt is a live route or a test decoy\n  (the benchmark.decoy=true label strongly suggests decoy). Apply Fix A or B.\n  Confirm the \"cannot merge alternative backend\" error disappears from logs.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Upgrade Procedure\n\nStep 4 — Determine the target version\n  a. Check the ingress-nginx releases page for the latest stable version:\n       https://github.com/kubernetes/ingress-nginx/releases\n  b. Verify Kubernetes compatibility:\n       kubectl version --short\n     Cross-reference the server version against the ingress-nginx support matrix.\n  c. Read the CHANGELOG between v1.14.1 and the target for:\n     - Any renamed or removed annotations (especially limit-rps, canary-*, rewrite-target)\n     - Changes to the burst formula (if changed, recompute and re-verify rate-api)\n     - ConfigMap key renames or removed defaults\n     - Webhook API version changes\n  d. Record the exact image digest for the target version (use the pinned digest\n     from the official release manifest to prevent inadvertent version drift):\n       TARGET_IMAGE=\"registry.k8s.io/ingress-nginx/controller:<VERSION>@sha256:<DIGEST>\"\n\n\nStep 5 — Patch the Deployment: image + arg cleanup + grace period\n  Apply all three changes atomically in a single patch so only one rollout fires:\n\n  kubectl -n ingress-nginx patch deploy ingress-nginx-controller \\\n    --type=json -p '[\n      {\n        \"op\": \"replace\",\n        \"path\": \"/spec/template/spec/terminationGracePeriodSeconds\",\n        \"value\": 300\n      },\n      {\n        \"op\": \"replace\",\n        \"path\": \"/spec/template/spec/containers/0/image\",\n        \"value\": \"registry.k8s.io/ingress-nginx/controller:<TARGET_VERSION>@sha256:<DIGEST>\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"op\": \"replace\",\n        \"path\": \"/spec/template/spec/containers/0/args\",\n        \"value\": [\n          \"/nginx-ingress-controller\",\n          \"--election-id=ingress-nginx-leader\",\n          \"--controller-class=k8s.io/ingress-nginx\",\n          \"--ingress-class=nginx\",\n          \"--configmap=$(POD_NAMESPACE)/ingress-nginx-controller\",\n          \"--validating-webhook=:8443\",\n          \"--validating-webhook-certificate=/usr/local/certificates/cert\",\n          \"--validating-webhook-key=/usr/local/certificates/key\",\n          \"--watch-ingress-without-class=false\",\n          \"--publish-status-address=localhost\"\n        ]\n      }\n    ]'\n\n  Changes in the clean args list vs current live:\n    REMOVED: duplicate --watch-ingress-without-class=true (was in original last-applied)\n    KEPT:    --watch-ingress-without-class=false (correct for this cluster)\n    KEPT:    all other flags unchanged\n    UPDATED: image to target version + pinned digest\n\n  Replace <TARGET_VERSION> and <DIGEST> with values from Step 4.\n\n\nStep 6 — Monitor the rollout\n  kubectl -n ingress-nginx rollout status deploy/ingress-nginx-controller --watch\n  # With terminationGracePeriodSeconds=300, expect the old pod to drain up to\n  # 300 seconds before the new pod is declared the sole ready replica.\n  # Total rollout time: drain time + new pod startup (~30s) = typically <5 min.\n\n  kubectl -n ingress-nginx logs deploy/ingress-nginx-controller --tail=50 -f\n  # Watch for \"Backend successfully reloaded\" and no ERROR-level messages.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Post-Upgrade Validation\n\nStep 7 — Verify controller pod health\n  kubectl -n ingress-nginx get pods -l app.kubernetes.io/name=ingress-nginx\n  # Pod must be Running, 1/1 Ready.\n  kubectl -n ingress-nginx describe deploy ingress-nginx-controller | grep Image\n  # Must show the new target image.\n\nStep 8 — Verify each Ingress still routes correctly\n\n  a. demo-app rewrite:\n     curl -s -o /dev/null -w \"%{http_code}\" -H \"Host: demo.example.com\" http://localhost/app\n     # Expect 200 (path /app rewritten to / at the upstream).\n\n  b. rate-api rate limiting — correct 429 reject code:\n     for i in $(seq 1 6); do\n       curl -s -o /dev/null -w \"%{http_code}\\n\" -H \"Host: rate.example.com\" http://localhost/api\n     done\n     # First request: 200. Requests over the 1 rps limit: 429 (not 503).\n\n  c. rate-health — unthrottled:\n     curl -s -o /dev/null -w \"%{http_code}\" -H \"Host: rate.example.com\" http://localhost/health\n     # Expect 200 always (no rate-limit annotation on rate-health).\n\n  d. Canary header routing:\n     curl -s -o /dev/null -w \"%{http_code}\" -H \"Host: canary.example.com\" http://localhost/\n     # Expect 200 from stable-echo.\n     curl -s -o /dev/null -w \"%{http_code}\" \\\n       -H \"Host: canary.example.com\" -H \"X-Canary: always\" http://localhost/\n     # Expect 200 from canary-echo.\n\n  e. Canary health path (no canary annotation):\n     curl -s -o /dev/null -w \"%{http_code}\" -H \"Host: canary.example.com\" http://localhost/health\n     # Expect 200 from stable-echo regardless of X-Canary header.\n\nStep 9 — Confirm no annotation renames caused silent drops\n  kubectl -n demo get ingress rate-api -o jsonpath='{.metadata.annotations}' | python3 -m json.tool\n  # All three rate-limit annotations must still be present:\n  #   nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/limit-rps: \"1\"\n  #   nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/limit-burst-multiplier: \"2\"   (set in Step 2)\n  #   nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/limit-reject-code: \"429\"\n\nStep 10 — Monitor events for 5 minutes\n  kubectl -n ingress-nginx get events --sort-by='.lastTimestamp' | tail -20\n  # No new Warning-level RELOAD events.\n  # No \"cannot merge alternative backend\" messages (if ISSUE-2 was fixed).\n\n---\n\n## 6. Rollback Procedure\n\nIf the upgraded controller misbehaves after Step 6:\n\n  kubectl -n ingress-nginx rollout undo deploy/ingress-nginx-controller\n  kubectl -n ingress-nginx rollout status deploy/ingress-nginx-controller --watch\n  # Restores the previous ReplicaSet (revision N-1, image v1.14.1).\n\n  Check rollout history:\n    kubectl -n ingress-nginx rollout history deploy/ingress-nginx-controller\n\n  Note: the Ingress-level fixes applied in Steps 2-3 (limit-burst-multiplier=2,\n  canary-alt resolution) are independent of the controller version and should be\n  kept regardless of whether the controller rollback is executed.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Additional Observations (non-blocking; consider for a follow-up)\n\n- ConfigMap data=null: all controller settings are at nginx defaults. If custom\n  tuning is needed (log format, proxy timeouts, keepalive, buffer sizes), add keys\n  to the ingress-nginx-controller ConfigMap — no controller restart required.\n\n- No resource limits on the controller container (only requests set). Consider\n  adding limits to prevent unbounded memory growth under traffic spikes.\n\n- No PodDisruptionBudget (PDB) exists. With replicas=1, a node drain will produce\n  a brief downtime window even after terminationGracePeriodSeconds is set. For HA,\n  scale to 2+ replicas and add a PDB with minAvailable=1.\n\n- --publish-status-address=localhost is correct for this kind cluster but would\n  need to be changed to the real external IP or hostname for a production deployment.\n\n- rate-api-alt-easy (benchmark.decoy=true) has no rate-limiting annotations, which\n  means requests to rate-alt-easy.example.com/api are unthrottled. This is likely\n  intentional as a decoy, but confirm it is not reachable from production traffic.\nPLANEOF\necho \"Plan written, size: $(wc -c < /tmp/plan.md) bytes\"","description":"Write the upgrade change plan to a temp file"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":20447,"cache_read_input_tokens":30688,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":20447},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c55de4f8-cd8b-4135-bcf7-a3df0f711d9c","uuid":"2d500771-b542-4b21-89f6-a298ceac9580","request_id":"req_011CcQ4nKarPsMrZWEAvdsXU"}
